<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-097-948  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 097 948.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 27 1989 v23 n8 p97(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Our personal perspective. (three generations of programmers)(Taking Charge) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brittain, William R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The last three generations of programmers each have had their ownvalues and work methods.andP;  The first generation actually wiredcircuit boards and programmed on systems that may have had only640Kbytes of memory available altogether.andP;  This generation doesnot take systems methodologies, programming standards, structuredprogramming theories or systems design seriously.andP;  They did notlike documentation but always got the job done with one or twoexamples of work that went beyond expectations, while the rest gotalong more or less informally.andP;  The second generation saw women inbusiness, database management systems, the need for interpersonalskills, structured programming and virtual operating systems.andP;  Thenewest generation faces a diversified world of programminghighlighted by the immature microcomputer platform.andP;  The problemfor them is where to focus their energies in this diverse market.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ProgrammersCareersHistory of Computing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>